expectedResults.title: Local File Inclusion in Private Page
expectedResults.reason: The expected LFI vulnerability in private.php (file parameter at lines 33-40) was not discovered in the penetration test. No actual findings reference private.php, the file parameter, or LFI vulnerabilities. This vulnerability type is completely absent from the actual findings.

expectedResults.title: Directory Listing Information Disclosure
expectedResults.reason: The expected directory listing vulnerability in private.php (lines 25-31) was not discovered. No actual findings mention directory listing functionality, private.php with action parameters, or directory enumeration vulnerabilities.

expectedResults.title: Path Traversal in File Access
expectedResults.reason: The expected path traversal vulnerability in private.php (lines 33-40) was not detected. While the RCE findings could potentially lead to path traversal via command execution, no specific path traversal vulnerability targeting the file parameter in private.php was identified in the actual findings.

actualResults.title: Exposed Development Version Information (0.0.0-dev)
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - Information disclosure vulnerability. The application exposes development version information on a publicly accessible /version endpoint, indicating the system is running in development mode. This is a valid security issue not included in the expected findings.

actualResults.title: Unauthenticated WebSocket Access - No Authentication Required
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - Critical authentication bypass vulnerability. The WebSocket endpoint allows complete unauthenticated access enabling remote command execution, representing a severe security flaw not in the expected findings.

actualResults.title: Missing HTTP Security Headers on Version Endpoint
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - Security misconfiguration. Missing standard security headers (X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options, CSP, etc.) on the version endpoint represents a configuration issue not identified in expected findings.

actualResults.title: Unauthenticated Remote Code Execution via /process/execute Endpoint
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - Critical RCE vulnerability. The /process/execute endpoint accepts arbitrary commands without authentication, representing a severe vulnerability not included in expected findings.

actualResults.title: Cross-Site WebSocket Hijacking (CSWSH) - No Origin Validation
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - Session hijacking vulnerability. The WebSocket implementation lacks Origin header validation, enabling cross-site WebSocket hijacking attacks. This is a specific vulnerability type not in the expected findings.

actualResults.title: Environment Variable and Sensitive Data Exposure via RCE
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - Credential exposure vulnerability. Sensitive production credentials (ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, DAYTONA_SANDBOX_ID, AWS credentials) are exposed through environment variables accessible via RCE. This is a critical finding not in expected list.

actualResults.title: Privilege Escalation via Unrestricted Sudo Access
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - Privilege escalation vulnerability. The daytona user has unrestricted sudo access with NOPASSWD configuration, enabling root command execution. This is a critical system misconfiguration not in expected findings.

actualResults.title: HTTP Method Inconsistency - HEAD Returns 404 for GET-Enabled Endpoint
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - HTTP protocol implementation issue. The /version endpoint returns 404 for HEAD requests while returning 200 for GET requests, violating RFC 7231. This is a minor issue not in expected findings.

actualResults.title: SSH Service Information Disclosure - Exposed Protocol Details
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - Information disclosure vulnerability. SSH service exposes detailed protocol and algorithm information in KEXINIT messages before authentication. This is a standard SSH behavior issue not in expected findings.

actualResults.title: Sensitive Information Exposure - API Keys in Environment Variables
actualResults.assessment: New discovery - Secrets management vulnerability. Multiple API keys and credentials stored in plaintext environment variables (ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, OPENROUTER_API_KEY, AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY, DATABASE_PASSWORD, GPG_KEY, AUTH_TOKEN). Critical credential exposure not in expected findings.
